    <mxCell id="k10note" parent="1" style="text;html=1;align=left;fontSize=9;" value="128 threads × 1 float4 = 512 / pass&#10;→ &lt;b&gt;4 passes&lt;/b&gt; (offset += rowStrideA=32).&#10;Each thread: 4 vectorized LDG.128." vertex="1"><mxGeometry x="420" y="356" width="300" height="40" as="geometry" /></mxCell>
    <mxCell id="codebox" parent="1" style="rounded=1;whiteSpace=wrap;html=1;fillColor=#f5f7f5;strokeColor=#82b366;" value="" vertex="1"><mxGeometry x="780" y="92" width="300" height="150" as="geometry" /></mxCell>
    <mxCell id="code" parent="1" style="text;html=1;align=left;fontSize=9;fontFamily=Courier New;whiteSpace=nowrap;verticalAlign=top;spacingLeft=8;spacingTop=6;" value="&lt;b&gt;identical body (float4):&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br&gt;float4 t = *(float4*)&amp;A[..];&lt;br&gt;As[..] = t.x .. t.w;&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;b&gt;k10 wraps it in:&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br&gt;for (offset=0;&lt;br&gt;     offset+rowStrideA&lt;=BM;&lt;br&gt;     offset+=rowStrideA)&lt;br&gt;&lt;br&gt;&lt;b&gt;k6:&lt;/b&gt; offset≡0, no loop" vertex="1"><mxGeometry x="788" y="98" width="288" height="138" as="geometry" /></mxCell>
    <mxCell id="note" parent="1" style="rounded=1;whiteSpace=wrap;html=1;fillColor=#fef3c7;strokeColor=#b45309;fontSize=10;align=left;verticalAlign=middle;spacingLeft=10;spacingRight=10;" value="&lt;b&gt;Both kernels load vectorized (float4 / LDG.128) and transpose A into As — the load body is identical.&lt;/b&gt; The ONLY difference: kernel 6 has 256 threads for a 1024-elem tile, so one float4 per thread fills it in a single pass; kernel 10 has 128 threads for a 2048-elem tile, so each thread issues 4 float4s via a strided loop (offset += rowStrideA). The loop form comes from kernel 9. All of warptiling's real novelty is in processFromSmem, not here." vertex="1"><mxGeometry x="20" y="400" width="1060" height="54" as="geometry" /></mxCell>
